4.46/5  rDev -2.2%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.5Canned 7/21. Consumed 8/6.
A: Pours a slightly hazy golden amber with a soft and inviting white head. Bits of lacing stick to the edge of the glass.
S: Grapefruit- and citrus-forward with supporting roles played by fresh, dank, musty herbs and caramel malt sweetness.
T: Sweet and malty start is quickly overtaken by an array of candied tropical fruits. Red grapefruit, pineapple, and mango flavors abound, ultimately giving way to an assertive piney bitterness on the finish.
M: Silky, creamy feel that makes this dangerously drinkable. Barely a hint of alcohol, aside from the malt sweetness I get up front on the flavor.
O: Despite its origins in the land of the Alchemist's Heady Topper and Hill Farmstead's Susan, Sip stands in a category outside of the hazy, juicy, hop-forward (D)IPAs that Vermont is known for. It doesn't seem to attempt to hide it's rich malt character, instead choosing to use it in conjunction with an explosion of sweet, fruity hop flavors. And just when you think you're drinking pureed caramel fruits, a resinous punch of pine brings along a substantial bitterness that combines with the sweet aftertaste to produce a decently dry finish. Overall, it's a very unique beer that truly succeeds in what it's going for. 1,251 charactersavas, Jun 19, 2016
