3.74/5  rDev -18%look: 4.25 | smell: 4 | taste: 3.5 | feel: 3.75 |  overall: 3.75JFresh21, Aug 04, 2015
4.23/5  rDev -7.2%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.25smb71481, Aug 04, 2015
4.59/5  rDev +0.7%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.75 |  overall: 4.5Tall boy can poured into HF wine stem.
canned on 07/10/2015.
Appearance: Golden yellow body with an orange hue.  3 fingers of bone white head that has good head retention and leaves spotty lacing all over the glass. Eventually the beer drops down to a thin cap.
Smell: bright citrus and tropical fruits are the main theme in the aroma department.  More specifically in the citrus profile you have a sweet tangerine and tart grapefruit; mango, papaya, and pineapple compromise the tropical fruit nose.    This smells outstanding and I will admit that I had my nose in the glass the whole time I drank this beer.
Taste: Upfront moderate bitterness level that just fades away pleasantly after each sip without the bitter bite becoming stronger which of course begs the drinker to take another sip immediately after swallowing the last. I prefer the aroma to the taste as the nose is more complex and interesting, but no question this IPA is quite delicious non the less.  Hops are citrusy, tropical and even slightly floral. Lots of sweet orange and tropical fruits provide the bulk of the hoppy profile found in this beer. This beer is massively hoppy, but you are not blasted with crazy bitterness that is found in most IPA's.  The floral flavors come in near the end of each sip and provide a slightly dry taste to the finish; mixed with some orange zest that makes this beer taste crisp and clean with juicy and sweet hop flavors on the front end and in the middle of the beer. Malt profile is bready with a little additional sweetness that balances out all those hops pretty nice. 
Mouthfeel: medium bodied beer with moderate carbonation levels. The carbonation is dialed in pretty well and abv is well hidden when this beer is cold, but as it warms there is an ever so slight sweet and booze presence. It is still pretty easy to crush the sixteen ounces from that tall boy can. 
Overall: Sip of Sunshine is a great IPA. Lawson's make some fantastic hoppy beers. Double Sunshine still rules the roost as the very best hoppy beer that Lawson's brews.  Bonus points for this beer getting packaged in tallboy cans; that is always great to see. I love the fact that I can't stop burping oranges after drinking this beer. MIght even be the best IPA that I have ever drank. 2,275 characters4DAloveofSTOUT, Aug 04, 2015
