4.4/5  rDev -3.5%look: 4.75 | smell: 4 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5Bigdoc91, Mar 12, 2015
4.46/5  rDev -2.2%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.5jw1978, Mar 12, 2015
4.52/5  rDev -0.9%look: 4.5 | smell: 5 | taste: 4 | feel: 5 |  overall: 4.75Just got back from a successful trip to Vermont.  So, might as well start drinking at 3:30 pm.  'Cause, that's what you do when you get back from Vermont.  Hey, what the hell, I woke up at 4 am, might as well start now and go to bed at 8.
First sip of The Sip ever, and I have high expectations.  But FIRST...let's clear some things up.  People love to antagonize the battle between Heady and [insert VT IPA here].  To be honest, what I was expecting here was another Heady clone, trying to emulate, but what I found was a completely different beer in its own right.  At certain points I will refer to Heady for clarification, but what Lawson's has created here is a beer of its own.  Props to them for creating something that lives up to the Vermont standard, and maybe even raise it, while not being an emulator.  SoS is SoS.  Heady is Heady.  Let's get over that now.  NOW...
A: OK, it looks like an IPA.  That golden/amber/orange color, opaque, decent head, all that jazz.  Fine.
S: What is dis...?  It's so fruity, but...I can't wrap my head around it.  It's not that typical grapefruit tangerine stuff.  It's like...all citrus but not quite...it's sweet...is it just fruit?  No...wait a sec... there is pine in there!  Plenty of pine, actually.  It's just so balanced, it somehow ADDS to the citrus.  It complements the perception of sweet citrus fruit, somehow.  I've wasted my smelling capacity and still haven't figured it out.  Props for creating something so delicately perfected!  It's pungent, yes, but that's not what does it.  It's that "wait, let me smell that again..." factor.  Very complex and balanced smell.  Whereas Heady is definitely, as they say, meant to be drank from the can, this beer is meant to be poured.  One of the most impressively created smells I've experienced in an IPA.
T: Hmm.  It's no Heady (read introduction for disclaimer).  Not quite the same as the smell.  It's very bitter relative to other 8%-ers.  Kinda creates a bitter grapefruit sensation, but overall the bitterness overpowers the sweetness that the malt creates and it is not as addicting to drink as others.  Better than a lot, not as good as a lot.  Right in the middle.  Still, that great smell is wrapped up in the flavor, and it's nice.  Just not as prominent as it is in the smell.  
M: Wow, this is thick!  Each mouthful is huge and drips down your throat.  Probably the thickest I've had of an 8% IPA.  Personally, I love it.  It doesn't chug, it is savored.  Perfect carbonation to complement the thickness.  
O: Sip of Sunshine is Sip of Sunshine.  It's a unique and expertly crafted creation in its own right.  It's not Heady, but it's not meant to be compared to Heady.  It's an amazingly-made beer and has great, unique qualities.  Props to Lawson's for further adding to the legend of Vermont IPAs. 2,823 charactersakrz47, Mar 12, 2015
