4.31/5  rDev -5.5%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.25 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.25Drank on tap at The Elbow Room, West Hartford, CT
Served in a becker
The beer poured a golden amber color and was topped by a small, creamy, bright white cap of froth. Solid head retention. The crown deposited a patchy latticework of lacing along the top portion of the glass.
Fantastic aroma. Super hoppy and fruity. Tropical fruit notes dominated. Mango, passionfruit and papaya came through strongest. Moderate citrus presence. Grapefruit was noticeable. Touch of orange peel. As the beer sat, the tropical fruitiness decreased and the citrus notes intensified.
The flavor profile was solid but not quite as complex or as smooth as the nose. Citrus notes were most apparent. Grapefruit came through super strong. Loads of orange and orange peel. Some mango as well. The beer was anchored by a semi-sweet, crystal malt backbone that was merely strong enough to temper the hoppy bitterness. Pithy grapefruit rind-like notes appeared in the finish. A bit of pine also came through.
The mouthfeel was lighter bodied for the style and pillowy soft. Super frothy and fluffy. The liquid contained a fine, zippy effervescence.
Aside from Double Sunshine, I find most of Lawson's beers to be overhyped and overrated. Sip of Sunshine definitely falls into this camp. I would be very happy to have this as a local offering but would not go to great efforts to seek it out. 1,369 charactersDamian, Mar 08, 2015
