4.62/5  rDev +1.3%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.75 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.5The pour yields a slightly hazy golden-orange with a pillowy white head.  Pungent ripe tropical fruits fill the nose, mango, guava, papaya, with a bit of stone fruit.  There is a fuzziness to the smell that draws you in, enticing you with the promise of the first sip.
The first sip follows the nose and gives way to overripe mango the most prevalent of many tropical fruits, floral hints, along with tangerine and orange marmalade.  There are honey and cracker undertones, but the malt is definitely in the back seat while the hops drive.  Nice and punchy yet smooth bitterness which leaves a slight dry grassy aftertaste.  The mouthfeel is delightful and it gets better as the beer warms.  
One of the most impressive aspects of this beer is it continues to develop and really opens up as it warms.  Instead of falling apart like many of its brethren, it soars to heights few in its class can reach.  Plenty of hype surrounding this fine brew but it stands up to all of it in my opinion.  I consider myself fortunate to be able to have access to this wonderful brew fairly regularly. 1,087 charactersOntheLambic, Feb 23, 2015
