4.94/5  rDev +8.3%look: 5 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 5 | feel: 5 |  overall: 5mmhannon, Feb 10, 2015
4.34/5  rDev -4.8%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4.25We crack a tallboy, pouring into our oversized tasting snifters.  It shines the color of a ripe Georgia peach.  A powdery, snowy two finger head of white sand colored bubbles adorns this liquid, standing tall and retaining well.  It is also highly reproducible.  Thick sheeted cheesecloth lacing is left around our glasses.  Chill is definitely apparent, as are some tight dots of sediment with the dregs of the can.  Carbonation appears to be mild.  The aroma is bright and natural, with hoppy varietals spanning citric to densely piney, bittering and serious lemon zest, spicy pale and earthy amber maltiness, fresh tomato acidity, pineapple and pear fruity mealiness, tin, warmed Granny Smith apples, green acorns, tight juniper stickiness, mineral-laden clay water, succulents, dried spaghetti, peppery spiciness, celery salt, and fresh spring dew.  The flavoring gives creamy pale and wheaty maltiness at the forefront of the sip, dried rye and soaked barley, intensely floral and citric hoppy wash, cantaloupe and bitter grapefruity pith, under ripe pear and white grapes, dusty wool, mineral and metallic simple ale yeastiness, dried willow bark and honeysuckle, organic well water, tangerine flesh, vanilla extract, fusel booze, and stale white chocolate peppermint bark.  The body is medium, and the carbonation is lightly medium.  Cream and froth are up there, and slurp and smack are nice as well, but leave little room for a crisp finishing pop.  However, the fact that it finishes so cleanly to flavor makes us happy regardless.  The mouth is cooled, coated, and creamed, with lingering bittering astringency to pull us into a mild pucker.  The abv is appropriate, and the beer disappears at a nice pace.
Overall, this is an intensely serious use of hops right here.  Through both the aroma and flavoring you get this wonderfully fresh, authentic, sappy, fruity, robust, and uniquely Vermont-garden quality to the hops.  They seem unadulterated in their clean bitterness, with enough energy left in the end to offer a respite of sweetness to the ultimate balance.  The finish is thus clean and easy to palate, all while remaining excitingly flavorful and organically bitter.  This muddies subtly with warmth, so drink on the chillier side.  Again, we would like to give a thankful shout out to Joe at CT Liquors for pulling this one out for us.  Initially, we were kind of surprised to see it in his hand.  Having had to drive up to Vermont to a random little store to even find a random bottle of their stuff in the past, we hadn’t previously been aware of their collaborative brewing partnership with Two Roads out of Connecticut.  Thankfully, my upbringing in the state brought us home for the holidays, and thus, this beer to our possession, but it is always nice to be surprised in this wonderful world of craft beer. 2,838 charactersTheBrewo, Feb 10, 2015
