3.85/5  rDev -15.6%look: 3.75 | smell: 3.75 | taste: 4 | feel: 3.75 |  overall: 3.75I've had this before but haven't typed up my notes. Here are brief impressions from a can (first review was from the bottle).
A: Half finger wide head. White colour. Nice soft complexion. Good consistency. Retention is about 3 minutes. Body is a vibrant copper.
Sm: Lemon, lemon zest, pale malts, fresh citrus, some skunky herbal hops. Mild to moderate aromatic intensity.
T: Lemon zest, herbal hop character, pale malts. Good balance and build, with plenty of subtlety. Hints of mango and tangerine. 
Mf: Smooth, wet, medium-bodied, refreshing, crisp, and approachable. Accentuates the hop profile nicely.
O: Very drinkable and enjoyable. Still one of the best beers in the style I've tried.
High B
***
Found my notes from Fall 2014. Shared by a friend in Austin, TX. 
HEAD: 1 finger wide. Fluffy and soft looking. Creamy smooth consistency. Nice complexion. No lacing. 5-7 minute retention.
BODY: Hazy unfiltered copper colour. Murky with orange hues. No yeast or hop sediment is visible. Appears well-carbonated, albeit of average vibrance.
The orange hues make it quite attractive, but it isn't a unique appearance. I'm looking forward to trying it.
AROMA: Orange citrus zest. Pale malts. Grapefruit. Bitter rind. Pleasant floral hop notes.
Very fresh and fragrant. Damned appealing, yet mild in terms of intensity. No alcohol, overt yeast, or off-notes are detectable.
Hops seem well paired to the malts. The freshness of the citrusy zest is startling. Faint tones of peach and tangerine emerge as I explore the aroma. A hint of mango.
The fruity notes are just fantastic. 
Not a soapy aroma by any means.
TASTE: Citrusy zest is fantastic as the aroma suggests, and it's beautifully complemented by subtle hints of mango, tangerine, floral notes, and even some slight grapefruit/rindy bitter bite. Pale malts provide the malt foundation, lending just enough sweetness to balance out the hop bitterness without overdoing it or tending towards cloying territory.
Impressively well-balanced. Nice depth of flavour. The freshness of the flavours is amazing, helping each constituent note feel distinct in the build. Average duration and intensity of flavour. Has nice subtlety. It's a good overall build for an imperial IPA, boasting impressive cohesion. It's a gestalt build, exceeding the sum of its parts.
My main critique is that the grapefruit bitterness is a bit too much on the climax, slightly disturbing the otherwise impeccable balance.
TEXTURE: Smooth, wet, soft, refreshing, and surprisingly light-bodied for such a high ABV beer. Complements the taste harmoniously. Supple.
Not oily, gushed, hot, astringent, or harsh. Very approachable.
OVERALL: While the tinge of bitterness on the climax holds it back from true greatness, it remains a damn solid imperial IPA well worthy of its lofty reputation. I could finisha growler in one sitting with ease, and would happily snatch this up wherever I saw it. Well worth trying. One to seek out when in Vermont. The freshness of the fruit is divine, but I'm not so keen on the lingering bitterness.
B+ / VERY GOOD
