4.58/5  rDev +0.4%look: 4 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.75 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4.5650ml bottle, dated 7.14.2014, I assume the delay in releases was due to bottle conditioning, poured into a Lawson's snifter.
The beer pours a lightly hazy, golden straw color, many bubbles rising from the bottom of the glass with a thick, soapy, white head that sits about 2 fingers high that has decent retention and leaves some spotted lace behind. The aroma is lovely, plenty of citrus, tropical fruits, juicy, fresh and crisp, with some wildflower, delicate and soft with light pine and grassiness with just enough pale malt sweetness to balance the beer well. The brightness hides the bitterness so well and the delicate nature of the aromas is just what I like. The flavors are right in line, lovely pineapple fruit, mango, grapefruit, lemon, delicate wildflower, a touch of bitter pine cuts down the citrusy and fruity flavors, but doesn't overtake the flavors at all and there is just a hint of sweet pale grain at the finish that plays very well with the fruit flavors. The mouthfeel feels a bit lively, more carbonation and prickliness than expected but it coats the tongue very well and has a nice dry finish.
Verdict: A damn fine DIPA from Sean and a natural extension of Double Sunshine. He is really close to replicating his master creation on a larger scale. The higher carbonation really seems to be the only thing that seems that different which is hardly a big gripe from me. Just a joy to drink, like it's predecessor. 1,440 characterskevanb, Aug 07, 2014
